  "relevant_summary": "Based on the documented evidence, tree thinning has distinct effects on different components of forest ecosystems:\n\n**Effects on Mature Trees:** Eleven of 12 studies found that thinning trees in forests decreased the density and cover of trees (Action ID 1209). Five of six studies found that thinning increased tree size, with one study showing mixed effects (Action ID 1209). One study found that thinning decreased tree species richness and diversity (Action ID 1209). Regarding tree mortality, one study found that thinning reduced the number of conifers killed by beetles, while two studies found no effect of thinning on bark-beetle caused tree mortality (Action ID 1209).\n\n**Effects on Young Trees:** Six of twelve studies found that thinning increased the density of young trees, while one study found it decreased density and five found no effect or mixed effects (Action ID 1210). One study found no effect of thinning on the density of oak acorns (Action ID 1210). One controlled study found that thinning increased the growth rate of young trees (Action ID 1210).\n\n**Effects on Understory Plants:** Seventeen of 25 studies found that thinning increased the density and cover of understory plants, seven studies found no effect or mixed effects, and one study found a decrease in herbaceous species abundance (Action ID 1211). Thirteen of 19 studies found that thinning increased species richness and diversity of understory plants, while seven studies found no effect (Action ID 1211).",
